Management of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany
Report on the audit
Preliminary remarks
Taxation is the main source of revenue for public finances.
The auditing of this area should therefore focus on the activities of the Courts of Auditors.
This applies in particular to VAT fraud.
This alone generates tax losses of an estimated €100 billion per year in the European Union1.
Already at the VI EUROSAI Congress 2005 in Bonn, participants pointed to the need for enhanced cooperation.
This will allow the Courts to exchange audit approaches and optimise auditing practices.
VAT is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.
For the first time in 2006, both countries' auditors carried out parallel audits in the area of VAT.
The audit report was published in 2008.
Since VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the Courts of Auditors is needed to assess fully whether the measures taken are appropriate to effectively tackle VAT fraud. EN.
The two Courts decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit.
