2. summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The Courts of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed on an audit of the management of VAT.
In the previous parallel examination, they had identified suspected cases of intra-Community transactions,
Which had been re-established as a means of testing.
On the basis of the audit findings, the two Courts issued recommendations on the management of VAT.
The aim of the audit was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented and the suspected cases identified should be investigated.
The audit also addressed other issues, including selected cases of risky intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of VAT receivables and the VAT audit of large enterprises.
In doing so, the Court of Auditors found that:
1. recommendations made following the previous examination
• Recommendation 1: rules for the registration of taxable persons should be harmonised within the EU
During the first audit, the Courts compared the registration procedures with the us in both countries and identified differences that caused problems.
The Courts therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxable persons within the EU.
This has also been addressed at EU level.
The draft revision of Council Regulation 1798 / 2003 provides for the extension of existing databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of U.S. debtors.
The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxable persons and their possible deletion.
The Court of Auditors expected Member States to agree on appropriate arrangements, in accordance with their decision of principle, to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the VAT system as early as possible.
The Member States reached political agreement on the final version of the draft in ECOFIN.
The above-mentioned common rules are no longer included, and both Courts regret this.
They continue to consider such arrangements important in order to prevent VAT fraud.
• Recommendation 2: monthly submission of summarising reports As a result of the first audit, the Court of Auditors recommended that Member States should submit the summarising reports (CMOs) on a monthly basis in the future.
The amounts of intra-Community transactions could then be reviewed in a more timely manner.
Council Directive 2008 / 117 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC on the common system of value added tax in order to combat tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has reduced the deadline for the submission of the MTC to one month.
In CZ, this requirement was implemented by a revision of the USt law which entered into force on 1 January 2010.
In Germany, the transposition only entered into force on 1 July 2010, which failed to transpose into national law the obligation to submit the MFF on a monthly basis.
• Recommendation 3: data comparison between VAT pre-notifications and the Central Financial Intelligence Unit in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to examine the merger of VAT pre-notification procedures and the Central Financial Intelligence Unit The German financial administration has responded to the recommendation issued by the Federal Court of Auditors establishment of a working party to develop possible solutions.
The work has not yet been completed.
The Federal Court of Auditors will monitor further developments.
• Recommendation 4: exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level During the first audit, the two Courts agreed that an effective risk management system would not be developed by a Member State alone may.
Successful criteria and elements or approaches of a risk management system need to be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.
If not, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.
The Courts found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems which have both strengths and weaknesses.
The nku examined the system of information exchange within the EU – EUROCANET, while the Federal Court of Auditors focused on German participation in the “Risk Management Platform ”.
