3. examination of selected intra-Community transactions, particularly at risk
The audit also included high-risk intra-Community transactions between taxpayers in the EU covered by the EUROCANET scheme.
EUROCANET is used to identify risk-sensitive taxpayers.
Member States may participate in this scheme on a voluntary basis.
CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data under EUROCANET.
From the point of view of an active participating country, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
As a result, no information could be obtained as to which suppliers with German VAT ID would have been classified as highly risky cases.
In the selected transactions, the nku found both normal transactions and those suspected of VAT fraud, including carousel fraud.
The Fä were able to examine high-risk transactions only limitedly, particularly in the case of so-called "missing traders," whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxpayer.
In case of suspicion of carousel fraud on imports and exports
It is recommended that customs and tax authorities work more closely together to monitor the nature of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final customer.
Germany and a number of other countries have refused to participate actively in EUROCANET because they consider that there is no sufficient legal basis.
The Bundesrechnungshof found that the German financial administration is using other instruments to identify risk-bearing taxpayers.
However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.
The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation,
It was created by Eurofisc.
The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should feed into the planned network to combat VAT fraud.
Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
Intergovernmental mutual assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.
Therefore, requests for intergovernmental mutual assistance in the recovery of claims in CZ and Germany are treated in the same way.
The Bundesrechnungshof and nku compared the statistics communicated by both Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
These statistics contained inconsistencies.
The two Courts of Auditors consider it appropriate to re-discuss statistics at EU level in order to avoid further inconsistencies in the future.
If this does not happen, the statistics cannot be used adequately for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should contain more information on VAT.
Analysis of detailed data can help the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.
Both Courts consider that Member States with a low recovery rate should endeavour to achieve at least the average recovery rate.
The Commission should assist Member States in doing so if they so wish.
5. VAT inspections of large enterprises
The Courts analysed the legal situation regarding the VAT audit of large enterprises in both countries.
In addition, they collected information from the financial administrations, which they considered important in this context, with a questionnaire.
The situation was clearly different in both countries.
The CZ has a system for selecting risk-related cases that includes a large amount of relevant data (e.g. information on VAT audits, balance sheet data, profit and loss accounts).
The overall effective management and analysis of VAT control can be achieved.
A special finance office for large enterprises will be established in 2012.
There is still no comparable system in Germany, which makes it difficult to control and analyse VAT control as a whole.
The German financial administration focuses more on the selection of individual cases involved and is based in particular on data from U.S. pre-notifications / U.S. declarations and MZs.
Different risk management components to be improved support the evaluation of these data.
