4. assessment of the management of VAT in selected areas
4.1 Implementation of the recommendations of the first joint review
4.1.1 Implementation of the recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of conditions for registration of taxable persons within the EU supported
On the basis of the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors has recommended that the requirements for VAT registration be adapted and new rules for the cancellation of registration in CZ introduced.
These amended rules should reduce the risk of possible tax evasion more effectively.
In certain cases, it was found that the VAT registration of taxable persons did not cease if they failed to comply with their obligations under Czech Law 235 / 2004 (hereinafter referred to as the "VAT Act").
So far, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted any amendments to oblige the Fä to cancel if taxpayers repeatedly fail to submit VAT declarations.
According to the Czech VAT law, the Fa may, on its own initiative, cancel the registration of a taxable person if (a) the taxable person has not made any transactions for twelve consecutive months and has not informed the Fa of the reasons for doing so. (b) the taxpayer has not fulfilled its obligations under the VAT law; (c) the taxpayer no longer fulfils the conditions for the taxpayer.
The first examination showed that due to the existing legal situation, Prague 1 must remove the VAT registration of "foreign taxpayers" 3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year if it does not register and pay ust in the current calendar year. they were obliged to do so.
Prague 1 often did not cancel the VAT registration of these taxable persons because the relevant provision of the deadline could not be adequately implemented in practice.
The problem was solved by the revision of the USt law, which entered into force on 1 January 2009.
Consequently, the Fa is entitled to cancel the registration of a foreign taxable person if he has not supplied taxable or exempt goods or services entitled to deduction in the previous calendar year.
Recommendation 2
Monthly submission of the MZM
On the basis of the first audit, the Courts of Auditors recommended the introduction of the monthly submission of MZs.
The Council Directive, which reduced the rate of delivery of MZs to one month, was implemented in CZ by the VAT Act, which entered into force on 1 January 2010.
The CMO must now be delivered electronically.
In addition, a MIP must be provided when the services to which the place of performance is to be determined in accordance with § 9 (1) VAT law are provided to a person registered in another Member State as subject to VAT.
This obligation stems from Council Directive 2008 / 8 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC as regards the place of supply of services.
Recommendation 3
Comparison of data from U.S. pre-notifications and ZM to increase the reliability of the MIAS data This Recommendation related to the German financial administration.
In its ATIS4 system, the Czech financial administration automatically aligns data on intra-Community transactions from the U.S. declarations and the CMO.
Recommendation 4
Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of VAT is an essential prerequisite for the smooth functioning of the EU internal market.
This is why the fight against us fraud is of primary interest and has received considerable attention in recent years.
The importance of this is illustrated, inter alia, by a study published by the European Commission in October 2009.
An external expert estimated the VAT failure for the 25 Member States during the period 2000 to 2006. after analysing the available data, the tax failure for that period was estimated at €90 to 113 billion. the EU-25 loses an average of 12% of their turnover taxes each year.
The estimated tax loss0 for CZ was 18% in 2006.
The first audit found that a Member State alone cannot develop an effective risk management system (RMS).
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each Member State.
As regards the RMS, the Czech Court of Auditors has examined the system for the exchange of information within the EU (EUROCANET).
Taxpayers within the EU selected risk-based intra-Community transactions covered by EUROCANET (see chapter 4.3).
The Eurofisc network aims to optimise mutual assistance in tax matters and to combat VAT fraud more effectively and to improve cooperation between competent authorities to detect fraud cases as early as possible.
Later Eurofisc could be used as a tool to assess the risk potential of intra-Community transactions.
The ECOFIN Council6 already approved Eurofisc on 7 October 2008, while adopting the principles governing the operation of the system.
EUROCANET, developed by the Belgian financial administration in cooperation with the other Member States and with the support of the European Commission and OLAF7, is a model for Eurofisc.
The purpose of the system is to detect risk-related transactions and to identify entrepreneurs involved in organised VAT fraud.
