4.4.1 Intergovernmental mutual assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic
The legislation on intergovernmental mutual assistance for recovery of certain claims in the EU is essentially based on:
Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to measures which form part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund and to levies and duties;
Council Directive 2001 / 44 / EC amending Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to measures which form part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund and amending Directive 2001 / 44 / EC customs duties and VAT and certain excise duties; and
Commission Directive 2002 / 94 / EC laying down detailed rules for the application of certain Articles of Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to certain levies, duties, taxes and other measures. "
The CZ transposed Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC by Law 252 / 2000 on intergovernmental mutual assistance for the recovery of certain claims.
Following the adoption of Council Directive 2001 / 44 / EC, it was also necessary to transpose it into Czech law and, at the same time, it was necessary to amend the aforementioned law.
In this context, the Act No 191 / 2004 on intergovernmental mutual assistance for the recovery of certain claims was adopted.
A new relevant legislation was adopted by Commission Regulation (EC) No 1179 / 2008 of 28 November 2008.
The annexes to this Regulation contain new application forms to be used from 1 January 2009 and the Regulation also makes electronic transmission compulsory and obliges the requesting authority to certify the conformity of all transmitted documents with the respective original.
The main principles of international mutual assistance for the recovery of claims are:
1. the principle of reciprocity applies;
Mutual assistance must always be provided only on request and on fulfilment of all conditions;
3. mutual assistance shall not cover claims considered as criminal penalties in the requested State;
4. the intergovernmental mutual assistance procedure for the recovery of claims must be carried out in accordance with the national law of the requested State;
5. in the recovery procedure, foreign claims do not take precedence over domestic claims;
6. mutual assistance shall only be provided for the recovery of uncontested claims;
7. the principle of recovery applies: the applicant State must use all the means available to it under national law to recover the claim.
Law 191 / 2004 provides for three forms of mutual assistance: information, notification of acts and actual recovery.
